5wy.title: Project outline: Intro to the Universal Property
5wy.clickbait: Outline detailing all the work required for a proposed Arbital Project
5wy.text:
[summary: Category theory is famously very difficult to understand, even for people with a relatively high level of mathematical maturity. Universal properties are perhaps the easiest important theme of category theory.

With this project, we want to produce an explanation that will clearly communicate this core concept in category theory, the universal property, to a wide audience of learners.]

Category theory is famously very difficult to understand, even for people with a relatively high level of mathematical maturity. Universal properties are perhaps the easiest important theme of category theory.

With this project, we want to produce an explanation that will clearly communicate this core concept in category theory, the universal property, to a wide audience of learners.

This page is an outline for the project, the below links are to pages within its scope.

1. The idea of [64t not caring about things except up to isomorphism].
- [4f4]
2. The idea that [5zt we can describe objects based entirely on how they interact with other objects].
3. Introduce the [614 category of finite sets], describing the empty set, disjoint union and product
- [3jz]
- [5zy]
- [5zc]
- [5s8]
- [5z9]
- [5zs]
4. Show how [5zr the empty set can be described entirely by its universal property].
- [600]
5. Show how [63m the union] and [5zv product can be described entirely by their universal properties], up to isomorphism.
6. Introduce a specific [3rb poset] category: [ $\mathbb{N}$ with an arrow between $a$ and $b$ iff $a$ divides $b$]. (Not sure about this one - maybe it already requires knowing what a category is?)
7. Describe the least upper bound and greatest lower bounds in a poset; in particular, in $\mathbb{N}$ under the divisibility relation, we obtain the GCD and the LCM.
- A page (or two) about [-poset_least_upper_bound] and [-65z] (these actually already exist! [-3rc])
8. Describe [poset_bound_universal_property the universal properties of the LUB and GLB]; compare them with the union and coproduct.
9. Wrap up by [universal_property_in_the_wild explaining that this kind of property crops up all over the place].

5zr.title: Universal property of the empty set
5zr.clickbait: The empty set can be characterised by how it interacts with other sets, rather than by any explicit property of the empty set itself.

5zs.title: Set product
5zs.clickbait: A fundamental way of combining sets is to take their product, making a set that contains all tuples of elements from the originals.

5zt.title: Object identity via interactions
5zt.clickbait: If we think of objects as opaque "black boxes", how can we tell whether two objects are different? By looking at how they interact with other objects!

5zv.title: Universal property of the product
5zv.clickbait: The product can be defined in a very general way, applicable to the natural numbers, to sets, to algebraic structures, and so on.

5zy.title: Finite set
5zy.clickbait: A finite set is one which is not infinite. Some of these are the least complicated sets.

63m.clickbait: Just as the empty set may be described by a universal property, so too may the disjoint union of sets.
